WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.800
said, I would like to introduce our next speaker, Simon Couch. Thank you so much.

00:00:09.800 --> 00:00:16.799
I want to start this talk off with a question that some of y'all might find a little strange.

00:00:16.799 --> 00:00:22.400
So for some context, let's start on some familiar territory. We're looking at an XY plane. We're

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:28.040
looking at predictions from a machine learning model, where on the x-axis, we have the true

00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:33.720
value of some outcome variable, and on the y-axis, we have the predictions from a machine

00:00:33.720 --> 00:00:41.520
learning model. This is situated in some context where we want to predict the weight of a vase,

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:45.799
and for some reason, our model tends to predict that the lighter vases are heavier than they

00:00:45.799 --> 00:00:51.439
actually are, and that the heavier vases are lighter than they actually are. So my question

00:00:51.439 --> 00:00:57.880
that's maybe a little strange is, is this fair? Maybe a yes if you think this is fair,

00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:02.840
a no if you think this is unfair, and a shrug is totally OK if you're like, I don't really

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:08.279
see the association. So I'm seeing mostly shrugs, and I would agree with you. This is

00:01:08.279 --> 00:01:16.519
a bad model. In statistics, we call this regressivity, where the predictions of the model tend towards

00:01:16.519 --> 00:01:21.239
the mean. We tend to think that regardless of the values of the predictors, the weight

00:01:21.239 --> 00:01:26.160
of that vase is going to tend towards the middle. So this is a bad model, but I don't

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:31.599
know that this is necessarily an unfair model. I'm going to pull a little magic trick now.

00:01:31.599 --> 00:01:41.239
I'm going to change the title and the subtitle and the labels on the axis ticks in this plot.

00:01:41.239 --> 00:01:47.239
This model is actually used in property assessment to generate property taxes. And what we're

00:01:47.239 --> 00:01:52.480
seeing is that the homes that are less expensive, we're living in some sort of world where houses

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:59.080
are between $100,000 and $500,000. So for those less expensive houses, we're tending

00:01:59.080 --> 00:02:04.639
to overpredict the value of the home. And on the other end of the distribution for the

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:12.440
more expensive houses, we are tending to underpredict the value of that home. So I'm going to ask

00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:19.839
the same question now. Is this fair? I'm seeing no's. And I agree with you. We're taxing different

00:02:19.839 --> 00:02:24.559
portions of the population at different rates only because of the change in behavior of

00:02:24.559 --> 00:02:30.479
this model. So this kind of gets at the first point that I want to make in this talk, the

00:02:30.479 --> 00:02:37.919
first point of three, which is that fairness is not just about statistical behavior. And

00:02:37.919 --> 00:02:43.000
folks that are working in machine learning who are used to being able to operationalize

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.720
our beliefs somewhat straightforwardly into evaluation metrics, we really need to take

00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:54.080
a step back and realize that when we're assessing models for what we believe to be fairness,

00:02:54.080 --> 00:03:00.279
we need to realize that we're coming to this evaluation task with beliefs. And those beliefs

00:03:00.279 --> 00:03:09.080
are going to translate into whether we think our model is doing well or not. So the same

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:13.800
model parameters can result in behavior that feels totally benign when situated in one

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:22.919
context and deeply unjust in another. So like I said, this is a talk about fair machine

00:03:22.919 --> 00:03:29.199
learning. My name is Simon. I work on open source R packages at Posit. And I specifically

00:03:29.199 --> 00:03:34.520
focus on a framework called Tidy Models. If you're a Tidyverse user, it's sort of a

00:03:34.520 --> 00:03:43.119
younger sibling to the Tidyverse focused specifically on machine learning. Every year we run a user

00:03:43.119 --> 00:03:47.360
survey to try to get a better sense of what our users want us to be working on in the

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:54.240
next year. And in late 2022, the results showed us that people wanted better tools to analyze

00:03:54.240 --> 00:04:00.919
their models with fairness in mind. So we formed a reading group at Posit, folks from

00:04:00.919 --> 00:04:07.279
different parts of the company across fields and academic backgrounds, sociology, statistics,

00:04:07.279 --> 00:04:11.520
psychology. We read a bunch of papers and we tried to figure out what software might

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:17.239
look like if it were to actually help people engage with the hardest parts of the process

00:04:17.239 --> 00:04:23.279
of evaluating models with respect to fairness. And we came up with a set of software that

00:04:23.279 --> 00:04:29.359
we feel supports people in doing that. So I'm going to talk about not just that software,

00:04:29.359 --> 00:04:33.959
but those kind of three hard parts that I mentioned earlier. And the first one, like

00:04:33.959 --> 00:04:45.000
I said, was that fairness is about our beliefs. The problem of the disparities in taxation

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:50.720
based on these assessment models is a real one. A year ago, I moved to Chicago. This

00:04:50.760 --> 00:04:57.760
is a report from 2017 about the tax assessment models that are used in Cook County, where

00:04:57.760 --> 00:05:04.679
I now live. This is one of many articles about this system in Chicago. If you look up the

00:05:04.679 --> 00:05:09.519
same kind of parameters in Seattle, you'll see the same things. And even two years ago,

00:05:09.519 --> 00:05:14.640
the New York Times did sort of a meta-analysis across all sorts of North American cities

00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:20.440
and found the same pattern of behavior where the rates of taxation were disparate across

00:05:20.440 --> 00:05:28.640
the distribution of home values. The second hard part that I want to try to underscore

00:05:28.640 --> 00:05:35.839
is that defining fairness is really hard. The translation of our values and our morally

00:05:35.839 --> 00:05:43.000
held beliefs into these mathematical measures that we can evaluate is not at all a trivial

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:49.880
task, and it doesn't do anything to resolve the differences in our morally held beliefs.

00:05:49.880 --> 00:05:58.839
So I'll try to argue that back to this home value example. So again, this is a bad model.

00:05:58.839 --> 00:06:03.959
It's a bad model in kind of a nice way where all the errors are correlated with each other.

00:06:03.959 --> 00:06:11.480
And so we have statistical techniques to correct for this. So one kind of argument that a lot

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:19.000
of people have in what makes a fair model is that a fair model should at least be performant

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:26.959
by our usual metrics. So earlier in this session, we mentioned R-squared and RMSE.

00:06:26.959 --> 00:06:32.260
So let's see if we can get this model as performant as possible with respect to those metrics

00:06:32.260 --> 00:06:38.559
and see if that brings us closer to something that feels fair to us. So again, because these

00:06:38.559 --> 00:06:44.720
are correlated in a really nice way, we can apply a statistical technique called calibration.

00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:49.600
If we're lucky, we end up with a plot that looks something like this, where the errors

00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:57.640
are independently and identically distributed. And so maybe this is better. Let's take a

00:06:57.640 --> 00:07:02.559
look and make sure that those errors are independently and identically distributed. What that means

00:07:02.559 --> 00:07:09.160
is that the variance and the mean of the errors is constant across the outcome, the distribution

00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:17.399
of the outcome. So it looks to be just about the case. The errors are similar for a house

00:07:17.399 --> 00:07:25.640
that's $100,000 and $500,000. And to me, that feels like exactly the problem. If I'm the

00:07:25.640 --> 00:07:33.880
owner of an $100,000 house, and I'm just as likely to receive an error of $50,000 in the

00:07:33.880 --> 00:07:39.359
assessment of my home as somebody who owns a $500,000 house, that error as a percentage

00:07:39.359 --> 00:07:53.000
is much more impactful to me. So maybe we can evaluate this model from a different perspective.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:08:00.160
The percentage error across the distribution, if that's consistent, maybe that's a better

00:08:00.160 --> 00:08:09.760
model for me in terms of what I think is fair. So we can train a model that optimizes

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:14.839
the mean percentage error across the distribution. It looks something like this. To me, that

00:08:14.839 --> 00:08:23.119
feels better. But at the same time, people that are so used to seeing these metrics like

00:08:23.119 --> 00:08:27.799
r squared or root mean squared error, that they might see that our model is worse. The

00:08:27.799 --> 00:08:33.000
errors are larger across the distribution. And so we see that those two interpretations

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:39.140
of fairness are in conflict with each other. And they arose from two different worldviews

00:08:39.140 --> 00:08:49.760
about how we should be taxing people and how errors should be distributed across the distribution.

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:57.820
So defining fairness is hard. This is kind of one of the most popular quotes from a recent

00:08:57.820 --> 00:09:02.119
meta-analysis in the field. Definitions of fairness are not mathematically or morally

00:09:02.119 --> 00:09:08.799
compatible in general. For the mathematicians in the room, there actually is a proof here.

00:09:08.799 --> 00:09:13.440
It's called the impossibility theorem. And it basically says that if we do indeed live

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:19.400
in a world where there are disparities between groups, then different definitions of fairness

00:09:19.400 --> 00:09:28.840
are impossible to satisfy more than a small fixed set of them.

00:09:28.840 --> 00:09:33.960
The last thing that I want to talk about, for practitioners of machine learning, we're

00:09:33.960 --> 00:09:40.400
very used to this process of evaluating our models with respect to performance metrics.

00:09:40.400 --> 00:09:46.400
And much of the work of machine learning fairness as a research field has focused on what it

00:09:46.400 --> 00:09:54.380
looks like to measure that performance with metrics. But I want to argue that thinking

00:09:54.380 --> 00:09:58.880
about the whole system is just as important because the metrics evaluate the model, but

00:09:58.880 --> 00:10:04.640
the model is situated in a much broader system. And so I'll try to argue that in this same

00:10:04.640 --> 00:10:11.640
problem context. Let's think about how the predictions will be used. In one model, we

00:10:11.640 --> 00:10:17.679
could say that you take your assessed value of the home, and then you multiply it by some

00:10:17.679 --> 00:10:25.679
fixed number, and that decides what your property tax is. I found this 0.9% on some web page

00:10:25.679 --> 00:10:30.760
in the King County verse, and then I went to a different web page and found a different

00:10:30.760 --> 00:10:35.039
one. So if you live in the area, you probably know what this number actually is or if there's

00:10:35.039 --> 00:10:41.200
an analogous number. But the idea here, at least to me, our model that is trained on

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:48.440
the mean percentage error seems to be the most performant model in that case or the

00:10:48.440 --> 00:10:56.960
most fair model. Where I live in Chicago and in most places in the US, there's something

00:10:56.960 --> 00:11:01.159
that we call the homeowner exemption, where if you live in the home that you own, some

00:11:01.159 --> 00:11:06.640
fixed amount of that assessed value is sort of wiped out. So we're shifting the distribution

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:14.520
of the errors down, and then the rest of that value is taxed at a fixed percentage.

00:11:14.520 --> 00:11:20.960
And so to me, the R squared or the root mean squared error, that seems to me like a reasonable

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:25.640
metric to use in that case, because it does better on the other end of the distribution.

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:31.719
That mean shift of the errors is more impactful for me. If I own a home, it's $100,000. If

00:11:31.719 --> 00:11:35.559
I own several homes that I don't live in, then the errors are sort of averaged across

00:11:35.559 --> 00:11:44.140
the homes. And so it's not as important to me to get those errors spot on in that case.

00:11:44.140 --> 00:11:51.479
Another thing that might impact our gut reaction to what is actually fair is the change in

00:11:51.479 --> 00:11:57.400
the value from last year. So if I own a $500,000 house, and this assessment from the previous

00:11:57.400 --> 00:12:04.400
year was $200,000 under, and now my prediction is accurate, and I'm paying $2,000 or $3,000

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:11.159
more than I expected to, is that change in the amount that I'm paying unfair? And so

00:12:11.159 --> 00:12:17.479
we even need to think about what that model looked like last year if we want to train

00:12:17.479 --> 00:12:21.400
a fair model.

00:12:21.400 --> 00:12:27.200
So I've tried to argue here that the metrics evaluate the model, but the model is one part

00:12:27.200 --> 00:12:34.280
of a larger system. And that larger system is just as important to us in aligning the

00:12:34.280 --> 00:12:39.359
way that we talk about evaluating machine learning models with our actual morally held

00:12:39.359 --> 00:12:46.239
beliefs.

00:12:46.239 --> 00:12:52.400
So I've tried to outline three hard parts, is what I call them, of machine learning fairness.

00:12:52.400 --> 00:12:58.679
Much of the statistical software that's out there is focused on the second one, choosing

00:12:58.679 --> 00:13:03.479
and supplying a bunch of different mathematical measures that we can drop into our existing

00:13:03.479 --> 00:13:09.239
machine learning systems, optimize on the value of the metric, and tell our stakeholders

00:13:09.239 --> 00:13:12.020
that our model is fair.

00:13:12.020 --> 00:13:17.599
But I want to argue, or I've tried to argue to you today, that the other two parts of

00:13:17.599 --> 00:13:23.840
this process are just as important for actually aligning our beliefs with our machine learning

00:13:23.840 --> 00:13:28.599
systems. And I would encourage you to choose tools that support thinking about the hard

00:13:28.599 --> 00:13:30.400
parts.

00:13:30.400 --> 00:13:36.200
If you're interested in checking out the tidy models, there's a book by Max Kuhn and Julia

00:13:36.200 --> 00:13:40.719
Silgi called Tidy Modeling with R. That's a great place to get started with machine

00:13:40.719 --> 00:13:44.119
learning in R.

00:13:44.119 --> 00:13:50.799
On the tidymodels.org website, we have all sorts of long-form documentation pieces. And

00:13:50.799 --> 00:13:57.320
recently, I wrote two long-form analysis kind of demonstrating what it looks like to have

00:13:57.320 --> 00:14:02.440
fairness in mind while you're analyzing machine learning models.

00:14:02.440 --> 00:14:08.440
Links to both of these websites and to these articles, specifically the source code for

00:14:08.440 --> 00:14:14.799
these slides and different works that I've cited in this talk, are at github.com slash

00:14:14.799 --> 00:14:21.919
simonpcouch slash cascadia-24. I'll give folks a second to write that down if they want to.

00:14:21.919 --> 00:14:26.599
But I just want to say I'm very grateful to be here, very grateful for the labor of the

00:14:26.599 --> 00:14:32.599
folks that brought us together. And I have some hype stickers if you want to find me.

00:14:32.599 --> 00:14:32.840
Thank you.

